WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.680
Awesome. Thank you, Sam, and welcome, everyone. We're really excited to have this kind of

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:19.120
pre-rstudio global session. So as another person from rstudio, just really glad to have

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:24.600
you all here, and thanks for taking part of your week to spend time with us. So I'm going

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:29.840
to jump right in. We only got a couple of minutes here. The kind of first thing I want

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:34.799
to do is talk a little bit about, conceptually, how we think about data science here at rstudio,

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:38.160
how that applies to pharma, and then we'll look at some of the exciting updates that

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:45.720
we're making to support that conceptual framework. So data science, we like to talk about it

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:48.240
as kind of a journey. You start out with this hypothesis.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:55.480
Do you mind presenting your screen so that it's full screen? We can see the slides. Thank

00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:57.279
you. Sorry about that.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:06.559
Yeah, no worries. So we think about data science as a journey. It's a very iterative process,

00:01:06.559 --> 00:01:14.400
as I'm sure you're all aware. It starts with a hypothesis. There's development and data

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:20.120
involved in that development. There's collaboration with others, with other teams, other stakeholders,

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:26.680
and then at the end, it's some type of deliverable, whether that's automation or a handoff to

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:32.199
the FDA. And so in pharma, oftentimes, what this looks like is something like early-stage

00:01:32.199 --> 00:01:39.680
research, where you're developing that hypothesis that might evolve into a full-blown experimental

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:46.760
design and trial, and then into something like a report or a submission. It might look

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:53.199
more like manufacturing or marketing. Those are also key parts of the pharma journey,

00:01:53.199 --> 00:01:58.400
determining some type of objective, and then iterating to decide if that was the right

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:03.839
objective, maybe coming up with models and doing production scoring. And so there's a

00:02:03.839 --> 00:02:09.520
lot of different ways this kind of journey can be realized in the pharmaceutical space.

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:13.279
What I want to show you today is how we're building tools to help and where those tools

00:02:13.279 --> 00:02:19.199
fit into the different parts of this journey. So on the top, you have some major updates

00:02:19.199 --> 00:02:25.600
we've released in the last year to RStudio's professional products. So in the development

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:32.000
side, we've done a lot of work to ensure that RStudio scales as your data and the richness

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.360
of that data grows by allowing you to tap into things like the cloud. In the middle

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:42.479
part there, where you're thinking about collaboration and iteration, we've done a lot of work in

00:02:42.479 --> 00:02:47.960
a tool called RStudio Connect to help you dynamically share content. And then when it

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:52.919
comes to hardening and automation, we've done a lot of work in a product called Package

00:02:52.919 --> 00:02:58.839
Manager to ensure that whether you're doing analysis in R or in Python, whether it's using

00:02:58.839 --> 00:03:04.279
CRAN or Bioconductor, that you have the correct packages and dependencies that you need to

00:03:04.279 --> 00:03:09.639
be really certain that your work is reproducible and reliable. So those are the things in blue.

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:15.080
Those are kind of all available today as part of RStudio Team, which is that professional

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:20.039
platform for doing data science that you'll hear a little bit about this week. But on

00:03:20.039 --> 00:03:23.800
the bottom, maybe more exciting are some of the developments specifically in the open

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:29.000
source community that we've partnered with pharmaceuticals, the companies to kind of

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.960
bring to really support the workflows that you're doing day to day. So the big one that

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:41.240
we're going to look at today is this new kind of reimagined R Markdown. It's actually helpful

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:48.119
throughout the journey of creating hypotheses, collaborating and sharing. So we're going to

00:03:48.119 --> 00:03:53.720
spend some time looking at that. There's new packages for the middle layer of work where

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.199
building models, specifically tidy models, is going to be a major part of the RStudio

00:03:58.199 --> 00:04:03.399
conference. There's some work on Shiny in R Markdown that's being done. One example of

00:04:03.399 --> 00:04:09.240
that work is the thematic package. And then on the far end here, something that's really

00:04:09.479 --> 00:04:15.479
specific to the pharmaceutical space is the work that we're doing around validated submissions.

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:20.600
And so one key element of that work is a tool called GT, which is an R package for creating

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:27.480
tables, and then some work around validation and how different platforms and tools that

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:33.480
are supportive of submission can be validated. So let's drill into a few of those specifically,

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:39.239
and then actually kind of look at what's new. So kind of going actually backwards,

00:04:39.239 --> 00:04:45.640
we'll start with those validation documents I mentioned. These are documents that outline

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:51.640
for packages that are affiliated with RStudio. So things like Shiny in R Markdown, tidyverse,

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:58.600
tidy models, as well as RStudio team, those professional products. These documents outline

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:05.399
how to think about their software development lifecycle for compliance. So if your QA team has

00:05:05.399 --> 00:05:10.440
ever asked you, how can we be sure that R is producing valid and correct results?

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:17.559
That's a big question. R is a huge ecosystem. Some of the later presentations today are going to

00:05:17.559 --> 00:05:21.880
talk through how to think about answering that question. But we're excited to announce

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:28.519
some documents that hopefully will just answer that question for you for these RStudio affiliated

00:05:28.519 --> 00:05:34.359
packages. So be sure to check those documents out. We won't read through them today. That'd

00:05:34.359 --> 00:05:39.160
take a lot more than the couple of minutes we have left. The second thing that I wanted to

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:45.720
kind of mention, we talked about in the submission space, it's really critical that you have a package

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:52.040
management solution. And so RStudio offers RStudio Package Manager as one option there.

00:05:52.040 --> 00:06:00.119
And we're excited to announce Bioconductor as a new addition to that offering. And so to just

00:06:00.119 --> 00:06:06.279
kind of quickly show you what that looks like. If you're using packages from Bioconductor,

00:06:06.279 --> 00:06:12.119
you might be familiar with this notion that Bioconductor does its releases about twice a year.

00:06:12.839 --> 00:06:18.920
And so Package Manager makes those same releases available to you. There's instructions

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:24.760
for inside of Package Manager for how to set this up. But one of the things we're really excited

00:06:24.760 --> 00:06:30.279
about is that previously there was kind of no way to keep CRAN and Bioconductor in sync.

00:06:30.279 --> 00:06:35.799
And so if you're using RStudio Package Manager, you can actually go ahead and keep those two things

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:41.559
in sync so that as your Bioconductor packages install packages from CRAN,

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:46.119
you'll be guaranteed to get the right results. And I'm showing you today kind of an internal

00:06:46.119 --> 00:06:52.679
version of this, but you can actually go to packagemanager.rstudio.com, which is a free

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:59.640
version of the Package Manager service. And that Bioconductor offering is available there as well.

00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:06.200
So if you want to source Bioconductor packages as well as a kind of frozen version of CRAN

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:10.040
that will match the Bioconductor release, that's available to you today.

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:15.880
So I know we're going kind of in rapid fire succession, but the last thing I wanted to

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:21.559
talk a little bit about was some of those changes in the open source ecosystem around

00:07:22.119 --> 00:07:27.480
R Markdown and some of the packages that work with R Markdown to create these beautiful documents

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:32.440
that you might be using internally or for things like submissions. And so I'm going to talk about

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:38.760
two things, an update to R Markdown and this package called GT. And so we'll kind of combine

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:44.279
both of those into a single demo. But before we hop into the ID, just to give you an understanding

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:51.239
of GT, it's a package short for grammar of tables. So it's very similar to ggplot2,

00:07:51.239 --> 00:07:58.279
which is the grammar of plots. And so what GT is all about is allowing you to write really expressive

00:07:58.279 --> 00:08:04.359
and flexible code for creating tables and then take that code and use it to render those tables

00:08:04.359 --> 00:08:11.320
wherever you need them. So the same code can be used to create tables that render to RTF for

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:18.600
things like Word documents or to render to HTML. And so that's kind of the concept. And I'll show

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:25.559
you what that package looks like and how you use it inside of R Markdown. So let me switch over to

00:08:25.559 --> 00:08:32.840
the RStudio ID. You can this is all open source, so you can use the latest version of RStudio on

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:38.919
your desktop or on a server with these packages. And basically, the workflow that you'll see

00:08:39.799 --> 00:08:45.080
is similar to what we're looking at here. So I have some data. This is just kind of raw data

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:51.559
inside of a data frame. And to turn that data into a table with GT, it's very similar to how

00:08:51.559 --> 00:08:58.840
you might create a plot, ggplot2. So you start with this GT function and then you add pieces

00:08:59.479 --> 00:09:04.840
to get to the final end result. So in this case, we're adding some summary rows,

00:09:05.559 --> 00:09:12.440
we're adding a grand summary of summaries, and then we're telling GT how to format the different

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:18.760
text cells. And so I'll actually go ahead and run this code for you, and we can take a look at the

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:26.919
output. So this is going to create for us a GT table. And by default, that GT table is going to

00:09:26.919 --> 00:09:34.200
be in HTML. So it's right here inside of our markdown document. And you can see kind of what

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:39.400
I had described. We start out with this data that's in a table, and then we're adding summary

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:45.880
rows, we're adding a grand summary, which is this top row here, and then we're doing some formatting.

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:52.200
You can see things like footnotes are fully supported, different sections of tables are

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:58.359
supported, you can have custom formatting, column headers, so a lot of flexibility in creating the

00:09:58.359 --> 00:10:05.000
table just the way you want. And that's already pretty exciting, but it gets even better because

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:10.840
with a single line of code, you can take the same table that we've created and save it to a different

00:10:10.840 --> 00:10:16.359
output format. So if you need this table to exist inside of a Word document, you can create that

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:21.400
version of the table that will then render inside of Word or inside of whatever other

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:28.679
format formatting tool you want to use. So that's the really kind of exciting update to GT.

00:10:28.679 --> 00:10:33.000
But I mentioned there was something else. So kind of the last thing I want to show you is this update

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:39.640
to our markdown. And the way it works is inside of the latest version of the IDE, there's this new

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:46.359
option to essentially render the document as you go. And so by clicking this kind of magic button

00:10:46.359 --> 00:10:53.080
here, what I get is an interactive editor for the R Markdown document. So our code is still here,

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:59.719
you can see our table is still here, but I actually have kind of the rendering of the R Markdown

00:10:59.719 --> 00:11:06.359
in real time. And so why would you do this? Because it turns out it makes it really easy

00:11:06.359 --> 00:11:12.760
to create rich and powerful documents. And so as an example, I'll go ahead and insert another table

00:11:13.479 --> 00:11:18.039
and this table will take a look at some of the features that are available here.

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:25.239
So as I type Markdown, that Markdown is going to be rendered in real time. I can even put in things

00:11:25.239 --> 00:11:32.119
like emojis. So there's full support for interactive editing. And you can even do

00:11:32.119 --> 00:11:38.760
things like render latex in line. You can see the preview shows up and then the output shows up.

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:45.400
So as you're writing, it becomes a really powerful way to create and see exactly what you're doing.

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:50.919
But under the hood, it's all still R Markdown. So I can always go back and forth if I wanted to

00:11:50.919 --> 00:11:56.840
to the original document that's just a plain text file. So we're excited about how all these

00:11:56.840 --> 00:12:04.520
things together can hopefully help you in your day-to-day work achieve that data science journey.

00:12:04.520 --> 00:12:09.159
And so I'll end things there. This is just a little bit of a preview, a taste,

00:12:09.159 --> 00:12:13.320
a sampling, if you will, of what's to come both today and at our studio conference.

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:15.719
So I'll hand things back over to you, Sam. Thanks for having me.

